cd /infrastructure

terraform apply \
  -target=local_file.kind_config \
  -target=null_resource.kind_cluster


Then check the cluster exists:
kind get clusters
kubectl config get-contexts
kubectl get nodes

You should see:
devops-platform
kind-devops-platform

Build your Docker image locally:
docker build -t flask-app:latest .
Load it into the Kind cluster:
kind load docker-image flask-app:latest --name devops-platform


Then run the full apply:
terraform apply -auto-approve

After it finishes:
kubectl get pods -A


If Promtail ever gets stuck from a previous failed release, clean only Promtail and retry:
kubectl -n logging delete daemonset promtail --ignore-not-found
kubectl -n logging delete secret promtail --ignore-not-found
kubectl -n logging delete secret -l owner=helm,name=promtail --ignore-not-found

